2":"1002","1023":"1023","0958":"0958","Dec 1016":"december 1016","1060":"1060","abt 960":"circa 0960","Eure, Loire, Rhone-Alpes, France":"Loire, Rhône-Alpes, Frankrijk","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk","Vérigny, Eure-et-Loir, Centre, France":"Marigny, Eure-et-Loir, Frankrijk","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"abt 960–1023":"about 0960–1023","0958–1016":"0958–1016","1002–1060":"1002–1060","0960–1023":"0960–1023","bef 975":"0975","1016":"1016","0960":"0960","1002":"1002","1023":"1023","0958":"0958","Dec 1016":"December 1016","1060":"1060","abt 960":"about 0960","Eure, Loire, Rhone-Alpes, France":"Loire, Rhône-Alpes, France","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, France","Vérigny, Eure-et-Loir, Centre, France":"Marigny, Eure-et-Loir, France","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Vergy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>verge</i> ‘rod, pole, or perch (unit of length or area); half-acre’ (Old French <i>verge</i>), perhaps denoting the owner of that amount of land.","English: variant of <b>Ferridge</b>, a habitational name from Verridge Wood in Frant (Sussex). The placename probably derives from Old English <i>fearn</i> ‘fern, bracken’ + <i>hrycg</i> ‘ridge’.","Catalan (<b>Vergé</b>): variant of <b>Verger</b>, a topographic name from Catalan <i>verger</i> ‘orchard’ (from Latin <i>viridiarium</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Thivierge","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Henri, Hermel, Lucien, Herve, Renald, Rosaire.","French: variant of <b>Thibierge</b> (and, in North America, an altered form of this), which is of the same origin as <b>Théberge</b> (see   Theberge  ). The surname <i>Thivierge</i> is very rare in France. Compare   Verge  .","History: Hippolyte Thibierge from Blois in Loir-et-Cher, France, married Renée Hervet in Blois in 1653, died in Sainte-Famille, Île d'Orléans, QC, in 1700. His descendants also bear another altered form of the surname, <i>Verge</i>."]},{"name":"Verges","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Raul, Carmelita, Gilberto, Jorge, Jose, Juanita, Lourdes, Nieves, Rafael, Ricardo, Vidal.  French Emile.","French (Occitan; <b>Vergès</b>) and Catalan (<b>Vergés</b>): from the plural of Occitan <i>verg(i)èr</i> and Catalan <i>verger</i> ‘orchard’, a topographic name for someone who lived near an orchard or garden, or an occupational name for someone who was employed in one (see   Verge   3 and   Verdier   2)."]}]},{"name":"Duke","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["In modern use this normally represents a coinage parallel to   Earl   and   King  , but it has been used as a short form of   Marmaduke   from at least the early 1600s."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Duke  de Vergy was born about 0960, in Marigny, Eure-et-Loir, France. He married Elizabeth de Chalon* in 0975. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1023, in Somme, Picardie, France, at the age of 64."},"et":{"abt 960–1023":"umbes 0960–1023","0958–1016":"0958–1016","1002–1060":"1002–1060","0960–1023":"0960–1023","bef 975":"0975","1016":"1016","0960":"0960","1002":"1002","1023":"1023","0958":"0958","Dec 1016":"detsember 1016","1060":"1060","abt 960":"umbes 0960","Eure, Loire, Rhone-Alpes, France":"Loire, Rhône-Alpes, Prantsusmaa","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Vérigny, Eure-et-Loir, Centre, France":"Marigny, Eure-et-Loir, Prantsusmaa","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"abt 960–1023":"noin 0960–1023","0958–1016":"0958–1016","1002–1060":"1002–1060","0960–1023":"0960–1023","bef 975":"0975","1016":"1016","0960":"0960","1002":"1002","1023":"1023","0958":"0958","Dec 1016":"joulukuu 1016","1060":"1060","abt 960":"noin 0960","Eure, Loire, Rhone-Alpes, France":"Loire, Rhône-Alpes, Ranska","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Ranska","Vérigny, Eure-et-Loir, Centre, France":"Marigny, Eure-et-Loir, Ranska","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Ranska"},"fr":{"abt 960–1023":"environ 0960–1023","0958–1016":"0958–1016","1002–1060":"1002–1060","0960–1023":"0960–1023","bef 975":"0975","1016":"1016","0960":"0960","1002":"1002","1023":"1023","0958":"0958","Dec 1016":"décembre